{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516545"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:44:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:44:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12661"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12661"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.06,0.11,0.08,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5134"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58904"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5134"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12661"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44313"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8853"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15352"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17297"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18357"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42794"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58904"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman attends her GP clinic with a few weeks history of general fatigue. She has a past medical history of obesity with a BMI of 31 kg/m\u00b2, and she reports irregular menstrual cycles. Her father was diagnosed with type 2 diabetes at age 50, but otherwise she has no family history of note. Her physical examination is normal. Her fasting blood glucose level is 6.2 mmol/L, and her HbA1c level is 6.0%. Other screening bloods for fatigue are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral glucose tolerance test","Fasting insulin level","Anti-GAD, Anti-IA2, Anti-ZnT8 autoantibodies","C-peptide level","Serum calcium, magnesium, and potassium"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with symptoms and risk factors suggestive of possible type 2 diabetes mellitus, including obesity and a family history of diabetes. Her fasting blood glucose level is elevated (normal \u0026lt;5.5mmol/L) indicating impaired fasting glucose, and her HbA1c is at the upper limit of normal, indicating potential impaired glucose tolerance or diabetes. In general, the following tests are considered to be equal in terms of appropriateness for diagnostic screening purposes: 2 hours afters a 75 gram oral glucose tolerance test, fasting plasma glucose,\u00a0and HbA1C. Based on the new diagnosis of impaired fasting glucose and the patients symptoms, diabetes cannot be excluded based on the available information and therefore, an \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral glucose tolerance test\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation option here for diagnosing diabetes. It provides a more comprehensive assessment of how the body handles glucose over time, especially in cases where fasting glucose and HbA1c results are inconclusive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasting insulin level\u003C/strong\u003E could provide information about insulin resistance but is not typically used for diagnosing diabetes. It may be considered in the context of metabolic syndrome or polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), given the patient\u0027s irregular menstrual cycles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-GAD, Anti-IA2, Anti-ZnT8 autoantibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are used to diagnose type 1 diabetes or latent autoimmune diabetes in adults (LADA), which is less likely given the patient\u0027s presentation and family history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC-peptide level\u003C/strong\u003E can help differentiate between type 1 and type 2 diabetes by assessing endogenous insulin production, but it is not necessary at this stage of investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum calcium, magnesium, and potassium\u003C/strong\u003E are not directly related to the diagnosis of diabetes and would not be the next step in this context.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) is a key diagnostic tool for identifying impaired glucose tolerance and diabetes.","HbA1c provides an average blood glucose level over the past two to three months and is useful for monitoring long-term glucose control.","Fasting blood glucose and HbA1c levels can sometimes be inconclusive, necessitating further testing with an OGTT."],"references":["The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. (2020). General practice management of type 2 diabetes: 2020-2022. East Melbourne, Vic: RACGP.","Eyth E, Basit H, Swift CJ. Glucose Tolerance Test. [Updated 2023 Apr 23]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532915/","American Diabetes Association. Diagnosis and classification of diabetes mellitus. Diabetes Care. 2013 Jan;36 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S67-74. doi: 10.2337/dc13-S067. PMID: 23264425; PMCID: PMC3537273."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44313"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12661"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]